# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: baseball-scorekeeping
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] In baseball, an **appeal play** occurs when a member of the defensive team calls the attention of an umpire to an infraction that they would otherwise ignore.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] To properly execute a live ball appeal, a fielder must, with a live ball, tag the runner or base in question and communicate to the umpire what the infraction was and which runner committed the infraction.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] Such communication may be non-verbal, implicit, or assumed—so long as the intent of the fielder is clear to the umpire.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] Contrary to popular belief, an appeal out is not a force out unless it is regarding a missed force base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] For example, if a runner from third base tags up and scores, but a runner from second base leaves too early, failing to tag up, and then is put out on the appeal, the run counts if it was scored before the appeal by the fielders.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] Rare situations with a viable appeal on a runner who misses his force base require the umpire to recognize an apparent fourth out.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] Umpires will only rule on legal appeals.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] A potential appeal is *viable* if the appeal is legal and the umpire knows that the runner has indeed committed an infraction and will be called out if the appeal is executed by a fielder.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] Suppose that runners are on first and third base, and the batter hits a fly ball.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] The runner on third tags up, leaving third base immediately after the outfielder touches the ball.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] The runner seems to score, beating the throw home, but failing to touch home plate.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] The runner proceeds into his dugout without again attempting to touch home base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] The runner on first base stays at first base, and action becomes relaxed while the ball is in the infield.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] The fielders now suspect that the runner left third base too early and also missed the plate.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] Suppose then that a fielder, with the live ball, touches home base and says to the nearest umpire, "I think they never touched home." This is a legal and viable appeal, and so the umpire should call the runner out and direct that his run shall not count.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] Since the ball was live (and indeed must be for appeals to be legal), the runner from first could have attempted to advance at any time during the appeals.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] If the defense attempts to play on that runner, their opportunity to appeal the runner from third base is lost, and the run would count regardless of any subsequent attempt to appeal.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] A member of the defensive team may appeal to the umpire when a batter bats out of turn.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] The umpire then enforces the penalty for batting out of turn, if any.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] The ball must be live for this as for any appeal.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] After the appeal is made, the umpire will usually signal "Time" and figure out whether the appeal is successful.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] The field umpire then signals whether the batter swung, and such a judgment must, by rule, prevail.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] The umpire asked is usually the first-base umpire (or third-base, if the batter is left-handed).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] The plate umpire is not required to ask for assistance if they believe the request is making a farce of the game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] If the bat barely left the shoulder of the batter and the catcher appeals the "no-swing" call, the umpire will probably deny the appeal.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] This procedure was introduced because it is commonplace for a plate umpire to be unable to see some swings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] A manager may ask an umpire to request assistance on other plays where another umpire had a better view, but the umpire is not required to do so.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] Such requests are common when a close home run or foul ball call is disputed, or when determining the accuracy of a close catch or no catch call.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/appeal-play] In such a case, the plate umpire would put a new ball in play, and after the ball became live by rule, the defense could appeal the missed base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An **application programming interface** (**API**) is a connection between computers or between computer programs.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] It is a type of software interface, offering a service to other pieces of software.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] A document or standard that describes how to build such a connection or interface is called an *API specification*.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] A computer system that meets this standard is said to *implement* or *expose* an API.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The term API may refer either to the specification or to the implementation.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] In contrast to a user interface, which connects a computer to a person, an application programming interface connects computers or pieces of software to each other.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] It is not intended to be used directly by a person (the end user) other than a computer programmer who is incorporating it into software.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An API is often made up of different parts which act as tools or services that are available to the programmer.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] A program or a programmer that uses one of these parts is said to *call* that portion of the API.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The calls that make up the API are also known as subroutines, methods, requests, or endpoints.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An API specification *defines* these calls, meaning that it explains how to use or implement them.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] One of the main purpose of APIs is to hide the internal details of how a system works, exposing only those parts a programmer will find useful and keeping them consistent even if the internal details later change.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An API may be custom-built for a particular pair of systems, or it may be a shared standard allowing interoperability among many systems.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The term API is often used to refer to web APIs, which allow communication between computers that are joined by the internet.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] There are also APIs for programming languages, software libraries, computer operating systems, and computer hardware.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] APIs originated in the 1940s, though the term did not emerge until the 1960s and 70s.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An API opens a software system to interactions from the outside.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] It allows two software systems to communicate across a boundary — an interface — using mutually agreed-upon signals.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] In other words, an API connects software entities together.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Unlike a user interface, an API is typically not visible to users.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] It is an "under the hood" portion of a software system, used for machine-to-machine communication.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] A well-designed API exposes only objects or actions needed by software or software developers.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] This abstraction simplifies programming.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Building software using APIs has been compared to using building-block toys, such as Lego bricks.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Software services or software libraries are analogous to the bricks; they may be joined together via their APIs, composing a new software product.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The process of joining is called *integration*.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] As an example, consider a weather sensor that offers an API.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] When a certain message is transmitted to the sensor, it will detect the current weather conditions and reply with a weather report.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The message that activates the sensor is an API *call*, and the weather report is an API *response*.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] A weather forecasting app might integrate with a number of weather sensor APIs, gathering weather data from throughout a geographical area.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] It represents an agreement between parties: a service provider who offers the API and the software developers who rely upon it.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] If the API remains stable, or if it changes only in predictable ways, developers' confidence in the API will increase.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The term *API* initially described an interface only for end-user-facing programs, known as application programs.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] This origin is still reflected in the name "application programming interface." Today, the term is broader, including also utility software and even hardware interfaces.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API is much older than the term itself.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] British computer scientists Maurice Wilkes and David Wheeler worked on a modular software library in the 1940s for EDSAC, an early computer.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The subroutines in this library were stored on punched paper tape organized in a filing cabinet.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] This cabinet also contained what Wilkes and Wheeler called a "library catalog" of notes about each subroutine and how to incorporate it into a program.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Today, such a catalog would be called an API (or an API specification or API documentation) because it instructs a programmer on how to use (or "call") each subroutine that the programmer needs.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Wilkes and Wheeler's book *The Preparation of Programs for an Electronic Digital Computer* contains the first published API specification.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Joshua Bloch considers that Wilkes and Wheeler "latently invented" the API, because it is more of a concept that is discovered than invented.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The term "application program interface" (without an *-ing* suffix) is first recorded in a paper called *Data structures and techniques for remote computer graphics* presented at an AFIPS conference in 1968.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The authors of this paper use the term to describe the interaction of an application—a graphics program in this case—with the rest of the computer system.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] A consistent application interface (consisting of Fortran subroutine calls) was intended to free the programmer from dealing with idiosyncrasies of the graphics display device, and to provide hardware independence if the computer or the display were replaced.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The term was introduced to the field of databases by C.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Date in a 1974 paper called *The Relational and Network Approaches: Comparison of the Application Programming Interface*.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An API became a part of the ANSI/SPARC framework for database management systems.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] This framework treated the application programming interface separately from other interfaces, such as the query interface.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Database professionals in the 1970s observed these different interfaces could be combined; a sufficiently rich application interface could support the other interfaces as well.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] This observation led to APIs that supported all types of programming, not just application programming.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] By 1990, the API was defined simply as "a set of services available to a programmer for performing certain tasks" by technologist Carl Malamud.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The idea of the API was expanded again with the dawn of remote procedure calls and web APIs.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] As computer networks became common in the 1970s and 80s, programmers wanted to call libraries located not only on their local computers, but on computers located elsewhere.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] These remote procedure calls were well supported by the Java language in particular.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] In the 1990s, with the spread of the internet, standards like CORBA, COM, and DCOM competed to become the most common way to expose API services.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] XML and JSON web APIs saw widespread commercial adoption beginning in 2000 and continuing as of 2021.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The web API is now the most common meaning of the term API.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The Semantic Web proposed by Tim Berners-Lee in 2001 included "semantic APIs" that recast the API as an open, distributed data interface rather than a software behavior interface.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Proprietary interfaces and agents became more widespread than open ones, but the idea of the API as a data interface took hold.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Because web APIs are widely used to exchange data of all kinds online, API has become a broad term describing much of the communication on the internet.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] When used in this way, the term API has overlap in meaning with the term communication protocol.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The interface to a software library is one type of API.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The API describes and prescribes the "expected behavior" (a specification) while the library is an "actual implementation" of this set of rules.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] A single API can have multiple implementations (or none, being abstract) in the form of different libraries that share the same programming interface.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The separation of the API from its implementation can allow programs written in one language to use a library written in another.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] For example, because Scala and Java compile to compatible bytecode, Scala developers can take advantage of any Java API.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] API use can vary depending on the type of programming language involved.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An API for a procedural language such as Lua could consist primarily of basic routines to execute code, manipulate data or handle errors while an API for an object-oriented language, such as Java, would provide a specification of classes and its class methods.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] By mapping the features and capabilities of one language to an interface implemented in another language, a language binding allows a library or service written in one language to be used when developing in another language.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Tools such as SWIG and F2PY, a Fortran-to-Python interface generator, facilitate the creation of such interfaces.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Moreover, the overall program flow of control can be out of the control of the caller and in the framework's hands by inversion of control or a similar mechanism.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An API can specify the interface between an application and the operating system.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] POSIX, for example, specifies a set of common APIs that aim to enable an application written for a POSIX conformant operating system to be compiled for another POSIX conformant operating system.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Linux and Berkeley Software Distribution are examples of operating systems that implement the POSIX APIs.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Microsoft has shown a strong commitment to a backward-compatible API, particularly within its Windows API (Win32) library, so older applications may run on newer versions of Windows using an executable-specific setting called "Compatibility Mode".
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] How much Microsoft developers' access to the company's operating systems' internal APIs is an advantage is unclear.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Shaffer of *Technologic Computer Letter* in 1987 compared the situation to a baseball game in which "Microsoft owns all the bats and the field", and large vendors like Lotus Development and Ashton-Tate reportedly received information about MS-DOS 5.0 that smaller software developers did not.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Ed Esber of Ashton-Tate said in a 1987 interview, however, that Bill Gates told him that his developers sometimes had to rewrite software based on early APIs.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Gates noted in the interview that Microsoft's Apple Macintosh applications were more successful than those for MS-DOS, because his company did not have to also devote resources to Mac OS.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An API differs from an application binary interface (ABI) in that an API is source code based while an ABI is binary based.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] For instance, POSIX provides APIs while the Linux Standard Base provides an ABI.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Remote APIs allow developers to manipulate remote resources through protocols, specific standards for communication that allow different technologies to work together, regardless of language or platform.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Therefore, remote APIs are useful in maintaining the object abstraction in object-oriented programming; a method call, executed locally on a proxy object, invokes the corresponding method on the remote object, using the remoting protocol, and acquires the result to be used locally as a return value.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] A modification of the proxy object will also result in a corresponding modification of the remote object.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Web APIs are the defined interfaces through which interactions happen between an enterprise and applications that use its assets, which also is a Service Level Agreement (SLA) to specify the functional provider and expose the service path or URL for its API users.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An API approach is an architectural approach that revolves around providing a program interface to a set of services to different applications serving different types of consumers.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An example might be a shipping company API that can be added to an eCommerce-focused website to facilitate ordering shipping services and automatically include current shipping rates, without the site developer having to enter the shipper's rate table into a web database.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Part of this trend is related to the Semantic Web movement toward Resource Description Framework (RDF), a concept to promote web-based ontology engineering technologies.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Web APIs allow the combination of multiple APIs into new applications known as mashups.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] In the social media space, web APIs have allowed web communities to facilitate sharing content and data between communities and applications.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] In this way, content that is created in one place dynamically can be posted and updated to multiple locations on the web.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] For example, Twitter's REST API allows developers to access core Twitter data and the Search API provides methods for developers to interact with Twitter Search and trends data.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The design of an API has significant impact on its usage.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The principle of information hiding describes the role of programming interfaces as enabling modular programming by hiding the implementation details of the modules so that users of modules need not understand the complexities inside the modules.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Thus, the design of an API attempts to provide only the tools a user would expect.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The design of programming interfaces represents an important part of software architecture, the organization of a complex piece of software.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] APIs are one of the more common ways technology companies integrate.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Those that provide and use APIs are considered as being members of a business ecosystem.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] An important factor when an API becomes public is its "interface stability".
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Changes to the API—for example adding new parameters to a function call—could break compatibility with the clients that depend on that API.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] When parts of a publicly presented API are subject to change and thus not stable, such parts of a particular API should be documented explicitly as "unstable".
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] For example, in the Google Guava library, the parts that are considered unstable, and that might change soon, are marked with the Java annotation `@Beta`.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] A public API can sometimes declare parts of itself as *deprecated* or rescinded.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] This usually means that part of the API should be considered a candidate for being removed, or modified in a backward incompatible way.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Therefore, these changes allow developers to transition away from parts of the API that will be removed or not supported in the future.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Client code may contain innovative or opportunistic usages that were not intended by the API designers.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] In other words, for a library with a significant user base, when an element becomes part of the public API, it may be used in diverse ways.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] On February 19, 2020, Akamai published their annual “State of the Internet” report, showcasing the growing trend of cybercriminals targeting public API platforms at financial services worldwide.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] From December 2017 through November 2019, Akamai witnessed 85.42 billion credential violation attacks.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] About 20%, or 16.55 billion, were against hostnames defined as API endpoints.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Of these, 473.5 million have targeted financial services sector organizations.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] API documentation describes what services an API offers and how to use those services, aiming to cover everything a client would need to know for practical purposes.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Documentation is crucial for the development and maintenance of applications using the API.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] API documentation is traditionally found in documentation files but can also be found in social media such as blogs, forums, and Q&A websites.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Traditional documentation files are often presented via a documentation system, such as Javadoc or Pydoc, that has a consistent appearance and structure.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] However, the types of content included in the documentation differs from API to API.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] In the interest of clarity, API documentation may include a description of classes and methods in the API as well as typical usage scenarios, code snippets, design rationales, performance discussions, and contracts, but implementation details of the API services themselves are usually omitted.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] It can take a number of forms, including instructional documents, tutorials, and reference works.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] It'll also include a variety of information types, including guides and functionalities.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Restrictions and limitations on how the API can be used are also covered by the documentation.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] For instance, documentation for an API function could note that its parameters cannot be null, that the function itself is not thread safe.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Because API documentation tends to be comprehensive, it is a challenge for writers to keep the documentation updated and for users to read it carefully, potentially yielding bugs.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] API documentation can be enriched with metadata information like Java annotations.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] This metadata can be used by the compiler, tools, and by the *run-time* environment to implement custom behaviors or custom handling.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] It is possible to generate API documentation in a data-driven manner.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] By observing many programs that use a given API, it is possible to infer the typical usages, as well the required contracts and directives.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Then, templates can be used to generate natural language from the mined data.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] In 2010, Oracle Corporation sued Google for having distributed a new implementation of Java embedded in the Android operating system.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Google had not acquired any permission to reproduce the Java API, although permission had been given to the similar OpenJDK project.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Judge William Alsup ruled in the *Oracle v.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Alsup's ruling was overturned in 2014 on appeal to the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit, though the question of whether such use of APIs constitutes fair use was left unresolved.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] In 2016, following a two-week trial, a jury determined that Google's reimplementation of the Java API constituted fair use, but Oracle vowed to appeal the decision.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Oracle won on its appeal, with the Court of Appeals for the Federal Circuit ruling that Google's use of the APIs did not qualify for fair use.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] In 2019, Google appealed to the Supreme Court of the United States over both the copyrightability and fair use rulings, and the Supreme Court granted review.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the oral hearings in the case were delayed until October 2020.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/application-programming-interface] The case was decided by the Supreme Court in Google's favor.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] In baseball, an **assist** (denoted by **A**) is a defensive statistic, baseball being one of the few sports in which the *defensive* team controls the ball.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] An assist is credited to every defensive player who fields or touches the ball (after it has been hit by the batter) prior to the recording of a putout, even if the contact was unintentional.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] For example, if a ball strikes a player's leg and bounces off him to another fielder, who tags the baserunner, the first player is credited with an assist.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] A fielder can receive a maximum of one assist per out recorded.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] An assist is also credited if a putout would have occurred, had another fielder not committed an error.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] For example, a shortstop might field a ground ball cleanly, but the first baseman might drop his throw.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] In this case, an error would be charged to the first baseman, and the shortstop would be credited with an assist.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] If a pitcher records a strikeout where the third strike is caught by the catcher, the pitcher is not credited with an assist.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] However, if the batter becomes a baserunner on a dropped third strike and the pitcher is involved in recording a putout by fielding the ball and either tagging the runner out or throwing to first base for the out, the pitcher is credited with an assist just as any other fielder would be.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] Assists are an important statistic for outfielders, as a play often occurs when a baserunner on the opposing team attempts to advance on the basepaths when the ball is hit to the outfield (even on a caught fly ball that results in an out; see tag up).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] It is the outfielder's job to field the ball and make an accurate throw to another fielder who is covering the base before the runner reaches it.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] The fielder then attempts to tag the runner out.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] This is especially important if the runner was trying to reach home plate, as the assist and tag prevent the baserunner from scoring a run.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] Assists are much rarer for outfielders than infielders (with the exception of first basemen) because the play is harder to make, and also because outfielder assist situations occur less often than the traditional ground-ball assist for a shortstop, second baseman, or third baseman.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] However, as a result, outfield assists are worth far more than infield assists, and tell more about an outfielder's throwing arm than infielder assists do.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] In recent years, some sabermetricians have begun referring to assists by outfielders as **baserunner kills**.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] Some sabermetricians are also using *baserunner holds* as a statistic to measure outfield arms.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] A baserunner hold occurs when the baserunner does not attempt to advance an extra base on an outfielder out of concern of being thrown out by a strong, accurate throw.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/assist-baseball] This can be combined with baserunner kills for better accuracy, as runners often do not try for an extra base when an outfielder with an excellent arm is playing.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] In baseball, an **at bat** (**AB**) or **time at bat** is a batter's turn batting against a pitcher.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] An at bat is different from a plate appearance.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] A batter is credited with a plate appearance regardless of what happens upon completion of his turn at bat, but a batter is charged with an at bat only if that plate appearance does not have one of the results enumerated below.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] While at bats are used to calculate certain statistics, including batting average and slugging percentage, players can qualify for the season-ending rankings in these categories only if they accumulate 502 plate appearances during the season.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] In addition, if the inning ends during an at bat (due to the third out being made by a runner caught stealing, for example), no at bat or plate appearance will result because neither were completed.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] An at bat is a specific type of plate appearance in which the batter stands at the plate intending to put the ball in play and get on base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] This is why at bats, and not plate appearances, are used to calculate batting average, as plate appearances in general can result in many outcomes that do not necessarily involve putting the ball in play, and batting average specifically measures a batter's contact hitting.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] Pete Rose had 14,053 career at bats, the all-time major league and National League record.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] The American League record is held by Carl Yastrzemski, whose 11,988 career at bats were all in the AL.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] The single season record is held by Jimmy Rollins, who had 716 at bats in 2007.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] Willie Wilson, Ichiro Suzuki and Juan Samuel also had more than 700 at bats in a season.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] 14 players share the single game record of 11 at bats in a single game, all of which were extra inning games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] In games of 9 innings or fewer, the record is 7 at bats and has occurred more than 200 times.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] The team record for most at bats in a single season is 5,781 by the 1997 Boston Red Sox.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] "At bat", "up", "up at bat", and "at the plate" are all phrases describing a batter who is facing the pitcher.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] Just because a player is described as being "at bat" in this sense, he will not necessarily be given an at bat in his statistics; the phrase actually signifies a plate appearance (assuming it is eventually completed).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] This ambiguous terminology is usually clarified by context.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] To refer explicitly to a statistical "at bat", the term "official at bat" is sometimes used.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] Official Baseball Rule 5.06(c) provides that "[a] batter has legally completed his *time at bat* when he is put out or becomes a runner" (emphasis added).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] The "time at bat" defined in this rule is more commonly referred to as a plate appearance, and the playing rules (Rules 1 through 8) uses the phrase "time at bat" in this sense.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/at-bat] In contrast, the scoring rules use the phrase "time at bat" to refer to the statistic **at bat**, defined in Rule 9.02(a)(1), but sometimes uses the phrase "official time at bat" or refers back to Rule 9.02(a)(1) when mentioning the statistic.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The **Automated Ball-Strike** (**ABS**) System is a system that automates the interpretation of whether pitches are in the strike zone in baseball games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] It is currently used by the KBO League in South Korea, and by Minor League Baseball (MiLB) and Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] In MLB and MiLB, it is used to enable player challenges of umpire calls of balls and strikes, while in the KBO League and previously in MiLB, it calls pitches automatically.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The independent Atlantic League first used ABS, nicknamed "robot umpires", during its 2019 all-star game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Umpires used earpieces to receive ball-strike calls using TrackMan technology.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Umpires could make a call based on the automated message, or could make their own call if the automated system malfunctioned or registered a call with which the umpire disagreed.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The Arizona Fall League began using ABS during its 2021 season.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The technology drew complaints from players and fans for its treatment of breaking balls as strikes even when they break and drop out of the strike zone.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Human umpires were obligated to make a call based on ABS, and players could be ejected if they contested a call, as with all ball-strike calls.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The Florida State League, a low-A league in Florida, used ABS in its 2021 season.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The Major League Baseball Umpires Association (MLBUA) agreed to cooperate and assist if MLB commissioner Rob Manfred decided to use ABS at the major league level, as part of the MLBUA's contract with MLB in 2020.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Five Triple-A baseball stadiums used ABS in 2022, and the system expanded to all stadiums at that level in 2023.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] In 2023, Triple-A baseball used ABS with and without a challenge system; without a challenge system, human umpires relayed automated calls, and with the system, an automated call would be used only when a team requested a challenge.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] In 2024, Triple-A teams that played six-game series first used ABS without a challenge system for the first three games, and with challenges for the latter three; starting on June 25, MLB announced that only the challenge system would be used.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] In 2024, 51% of challenges in Triple-A games were successful.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] South Korea's KBO League started to use ABS in its 2024 season.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Unlike in MLB, KBO uses ABS to call balls and strikes automatically.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] ABS was in place for Spring Training before the 2025 MLB season.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Thirteen Spring Training ballparks, used as home fields by 19 clubs, are equipped with ABS technology.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB implemented ABS as a challenge system; human umpires make initial calls, which pitchers, catchers, and batters may challenge.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB used ABS for the 2025 All-Star Game, with a similar configuration to spring training: each team had two challenges, which could be requested by the pitcher, catcher, or hitter immediately after a call.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Cal Raleigh, the first player to request an ABS challenge in an MLB All-Star Game, successfully challenged the umpire's ball call of a pitch he caught from Tarik Skubal, resulting in Manny Machado being called out on strikes.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Jacob Wilson was the first batter to challenge a call, successfully getting a pitch from MacKenzie Gore changed from a strike to a ball.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] In September 2025, MLB's competition committee approved use of ABS beginning with the 2026 season, with similar processes to those used in Spring Training and the All-Star Game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Each team starts with two challenges, retains a challenge if it is successful, and may receive additional challenges in extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] On March 25, 2026, Opening Day, New York Yankees shortstop José Caballero made the first ABS challenge in an MLB regular season game, challenging Bill Miller's strike call on Logan Webb's first pitch to him in the fourth inning.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Caballero's challenge was unsuccessful, and the strike call was upheld.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The following day, Francisco Álvarez, catcher for the New York Mets, made the first successful ABS challenge in an MLB regular season game, after he challenged a ball call on a pitch by Freddy Peralta.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The call was changed to a strike, resulting in the batter, Oneil Cruz, striking out.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] In May 2026, the NCAA baseball rules committee approved a request by the Southeastern Conference (SEC) for permission to use ABS as part of its conference tournament; it will utilize similar rules to ABS in MLB, except that teams will begin with three challenges instead of two.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] On May 19, 2026, Mississippi catcher Austin Fawley made the first ABS challenge in a college baseball game, challenging a ball call on a pitch by Mississippi pitcher Will Libbert in the top of the first inning.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The challenge was unsuccessful, and the call stood.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] As implemented by MLB, ABS uses Hawk-Eye camera technology, and a private 5G network by T-Mobile to transmit data.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] T-Mobile also serves as presenting sponsor for reviews.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Reviews are shown on screens in stadiums and on broadcasts for home viewers.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB has experimented with the size of the strike zone, a three-dimensional space defined in the official rules of Major League Baseball, as used by ABS.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The league started with a width of 19 inches (480 mm) in 2022, then decreased it to 17 inches (430 mm), the same width as home plate.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The top of the zone was 51% of a batter's height in 2022 and 2023, then raised to 53.5% in 2024 after pitchers' complaints.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The bottom of the strike zone was originally set at 28% of the batter's height, and has been 27% since 2022.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] ABS's use of height in its strike zone led the league to measure players more precisely, without manipulation by team personnel, in 2026; of the 430 hitters on Opening Day rosters in 2026, 225 had listed heights at least 1 inch (25 mm) shorter than in 2024 or 2025.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] ABS makes its decision when the ball is at the midpoint of the plate, 8.5 inches (220 mm) from the front and back, despite MLB rules stating that a pitch is a strike if it crosses any part of a 3D solid with home plate as its base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The ABS strike zone does not change based on the batter's stance.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] In MLB, only the batter, pitcher, or catcher may challenge a ball or strike call, doing so by tapping his cap or helmet immediately after an umpire's call.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Each team gets two challenges per game, but loses a challenge if an original call is upheld after review.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] In extra innings, a team that begins an inning with no challenges will receive one challenge to use or carry forward; it will not receive additional challenges if it has at least one at the start of an extra inning.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Players must make a decision on their own, without assistance from other players or team personnel, such as coaches or managers.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Unlike instant replay challenges, managers may not challenge a ball-strike call.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Challenges are not permitted while a position player is pitching.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] ABS reports pitch locations in increments of 0.1 inches (2.5 mm), although some players have expressed concerns about the system's margin of error.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB officials told *The Athletic* that the league has 95 percent confidence that ABS would a report a pitch to within 0.39 inches (9.9 mm), and 99 percent confidence that the location would be within 0.48 inches (12 mm) of its recorded position.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] During 2026 spring training games, the league said that the median margin of error on any given pitch was about 0.16 inches (4.1 mm).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB's internal evaluations of umpire accuracy use a buffer zone on the periphery of the strike zone, in which calls remain unchanged due to measurement uncertainty, but ABS has no buffer zone.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] In MLB, an ABS challenge typically takes less than 15 seconds.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Through the first two and a half weeks of the 2026 season, a nine-inning game took an average of 2 hours, 42 minutes to complete, up from 2:38 in the prior season, but still much shorter than 3:10 in 2021, the last MLB season without the pitch clock.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB started testing ABS because of fans' strong feelings about inaccurate umpire calls of balls and strikes, which can affect the outcome of games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] According to an MLB poll in 2024, 61% of team personnel (including players) and 47% of fans preferred a challenge system for ball-strike calls, 28% of team personnel and 30% of fans preferred not to use ABS at all, and 11% of team personnel and 23% of fans wanted full automation.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Players and managers have sometimes objected to ball-strike calls even after an ABS review, but doing so still risks ejection from the game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] "Nobody complains about anything anymore with the strike zone because there's nothing to complain about," said Toby Gardenhire, manager of the St.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Players observed that catchers could no longer frame pitches to try to get strike calls on pitches outside the zone.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Players in Triple-A have typically saved their challenges for higher-leverage situations; more than 8% of pitches on a 3–2 count were challenged, whereas only 1.6% of first pitches were.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] "Your heart rate goes through the roof", said Michael Toglia of the Colorado Rockies, about calling a challenge during his time in Triple-A.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Tyler Glasnow of the Los Angeles Dodgers said that ABS challenges were "the most fun part of the game" during a rehab assignment in Triple-A, because when a player challenged a call successfully, they felt "vindicated".
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Baseball broadcasters have redesigned their augmented reality strike zone graphics as a result of ABS.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] The league still permits broadcasters to show a box approximating the strike zone, but does not let broadcasters indicate where the pitch is when it crosses the plate during live action, to discourage viewers from signaling to players that they should challenge a call.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] After the first weekend of the 2026 MLB season, Jeff Passan wrote, "Not only does ABS work, it makes the game better." In the season's first 48 games, 94 calls were overturned, out of 175 challenges.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Fans in stadiums and television broadcasters had enthusiastically embraced the challenge system, leading Passan to wonder whether it should be used for all ball–strike calls in the future.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Former MLB umpires have suggested that current umpires would adjust their ball–strike calls in anticipation of ABS challenges.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] "As an umpire, what you're trying to do is not get overturned", said Dale Scott, a retired MLB umpire.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Joe West, another retired umpire, expressed concerns with ABS's accuracy.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Retired umpire Jim Joyce called ABS "the best scenario right now", because it is aiming to get more calls correct, and because it is used as a challenge system, not as a fully automated pitch calling system.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] In minor leagues and in MLB, the walk rate has increased significantly after ABS was introduced.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] MLB's walk rate early in the 2026 season was at 9.9% of plate appearances, up from the typical 8% to 9%, and on pace for the highest walk rate since the mound was lowered in 1969.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automated-ball-strike-system] Hitters began the 2026 MLB season by swinging on 46.2% of pitches, down from 47.2% to 47.8% in prior seasons, and on pace for the lowest swing rate in a 162-game season since 2014.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Ordinarily, a baseball game consists of nine regulation innings (in softball and high school baseball games there are typically seven innings; in Little League Baseball, six), each of which is divided into halves: the visiting team bats first, after which the home team takes its turn at bat.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] (Since the home team bats second, condition (2) does not allow the visiting team to score more runs before the end of the inning, unless the game is called before the inning ends).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Most of the rules of the game, including the batting order, availability of substitute players and pitchers, etc., remain intact in extra innings, although occasionally leagues and tournaments will place runners on base to start extra innings in order to speed up the game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Managers must display caution to avoid exhausting all their substitute players during regular innings, in case the game reaches extensive extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The rules call for a forfeiture if a team is unable to field a full team of nine players.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In Major League Baseball, home teams won about 52% of extra-inning games from 1957 to 2007.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] During this same time period, home teams have won about 54% of all baseball games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] So while the home team has some advantage in extra-inning games, this advantage is less noticeable than the initial home-field advantage.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Home teams tend to have the greatest advantage in run-scoring during the first 3 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] For the visiting team to win, it must score as many runs as possible in the first (or "top") half of the inning and then prevent the home team from tying or taking the lead in the second (or "bottom") half.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Because it bats in the bottom half of an inning, a home team wins the game by taking the lead at any point in the final inning.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Normally in such a situation, the moment the winning run scores for whatever reason (base hit, sacrifice, wild pitch), the game immediately ends and no other runs are allowed.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The term for winning in this scenario is a "walk-off" win (as everyone can walk off the field as soon as the winning run is scored).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The exception is if the winning hit is a walk-off home run; all runners on base and the batter must circle the bases on a home run, provided that they round them all correctly, so all their runs count for the final score.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Each extra inning simply repeats this scenario.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The East Asian professional leagues, NPB, and CPBL have a 12-inning limit before the game is declared a draw.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Starting in 2025, the KBO will have an 11-inning limit on single games and the second game in a doubleheader, and a nine-inning limit in the first game of the doubleheader (no extra innings).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Additionally, NPB games have a total time limit of 210 minutes during the regular season before being counted as a tie.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Postseason play has reduced the number of innings allowed.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Until 1986, the Japan Series had a 270-minute (4 hours, 30 minutes) time limit.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] From 1987 to 1993, it was changed to 18 innings; from 1994 to 2017, it was 15 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In the Climax Series, and in the Japan Series since 2018, postseason play rules are the same as the regular season in 12 innings (except in 2020 and 2021, when no extra innings were played in the regular season and first two rounds of postseason, 12 inning limits were used in the Japan Series).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In case of a drawn game, it is completely replayed as usual.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] A seven-game series can be extended to an eighth game or subsequent game, something that has happened only once (in the 1986 Japan Series).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Starting in the eighth and subsequent game in the Japan Series, the 12-inning limit does not apply, and the game is continued until a winner is decided.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Since 2021, a modified 12-inning limit is used in such games; beginning in the 13th inning, the two-runner WBSC tiebreaker will be implemented, similar to the current high school tournament rule.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The two batters in the batting order before the player at bat will take first and second base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Tie games are discarded when calculating winning percentages since 2002, except for 2008 when it was counted as a loss in the league's standings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] From the league's formation in 1982 until 2001, they counted as half a win.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] For CPBL postseason games, the 12-inning limit does not apply and the games will continue until a winner is decided.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest game to be played took place during 2009 Taiwan Series, where in Game 6 the Brother Elephants defeated Uni-President 7-Eleven Lions 5 to 4 after 17 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In the 11th inning, the manager selects anywhere in the batting order to start the inning, regardless of the last player put out.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The batter immediately preceding this newly designated leadoff man becomes a runner on first base, and the next preceding batter is placed on second base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In subsequent innings, the batting order continues as normal, but the two players preceding the player scheduled to lead off (or substitutes for those players) the inning start on second and first.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] This has also been adopted by European leagues Division de Honor (Spain), Italian Baseball League, and Honkbal Hoofdklasse (Netherlands).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Since the 2009 edition, a modified form of the rule has been used for the World Baseball Classic.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Unlike the standard rule, the batting order may not start from a different place.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Through the 2013 edition, the first inning in which teams started with runners on first and second was the 13th.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The rule was not used in either the 2009 or 2013 editions because no game lasted more than 11 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] For the 2017 World Baseball Classic, the rule was modified to use extra runners for the first time in the 11th inning, and it would see its first use in a second-round game between Japan and the Netherlands at the Tokyo Dome.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Japan won that game thanks to a sacrifice bunt and a 2-run hit.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In international softball, a special extra innings rule starts immediately after regulation.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Each team begins their half of the inning with a runner on second base (the last player to be put out).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] This increases the odds that teams will score and ensures a faster resolution.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] There is a drawback, though, in that the home team has a major advantage in batting second.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Should the visiting team fail to score, all the home team must do to win is, for example, get a successful bunt and sacrifice fly to score the winning run, though a similar advantage exists in all extra-inning contests just not to that extent.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] This rule is also used in certain NCAA college conferences, usually applied after one or two extra innings where the "international tiebreaker" is not used.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] During spring training in Major League Baseball (MLB), most games are played for the regulation nine innings only; if the game is tied after nine innings, the game is over and the tie stands.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] There are multiple reasons for this brevity.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Players are getting back into shape after the off-season, so shorter games help reduce injuries from overexertion.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] During spring training, teams often travel on a daily basis, so they need time to be able to travel to their next game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Lastly, there are no prizes or penalties associated with a team's preseason record, so there is no need for a definitive winner in each game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] However, there have still been extra inning games in spring training, with the most recent one being on March 30, 2022, with the Houston Astros beating the New York Mets 5–3 in 10 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Usually if extra innings are played, the game will be called after the 10th inning for the above-mentioned reasons.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In 2020, MLB implemented the WBSC softball version of the extra innings rule where each half-inning during extra innings is started with a runner on second base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] As with the earlier WBSC rule, the objective is to increase scoring opportunities and shorten extra inning games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The batting order does not change, as the runner placed on second base is normally the player who, in the batting order, immediately precedes the batter leading off the inning.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] On July 24, 2020, the Oakland Athletics defeated the Los Angeles Angels, 7–3, in the first MLB extra-inning game played using this rule.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The rule increased the percentage of extra inning games ending in the 10th inning from 43.9% during the 2019 season to 69.1% during the 2020 season.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The rule was later extended into the 2021 and 2022 seasons and was made permanent beginning with the 2023 season.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The ghost runner is also referred to as the "Manfred Man," an allusion to the rule having been implemented during Commissioner Rob Manfred's tenure, and a play on the name of the British musician Manfred Mann.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] However, the rule is based on the international rule for tournaments, which has been used as early as 2008.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Extra runners are not used in MLB postseason games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Postseason games that last beyond nine innings begin all extra innings without any runner being placed on base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] There are nine regulation innings in a professional baseball game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The record for the most innings played in a single professional game is 33, which occurred in 1981 in a Minor League Baseball game between the Pawtucket Red Sox and the Rochester Red Wings, at the time the Triple-A affiliates of the Boston Red Sox and the Baltimore Orioles, respectively.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Each team had a future Hall of Famer on its roster: Wade Boggs for Pawtucket and Cal Ripken Jr. for Rochester.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest game by innings in Major League Baseball was a 1–1 tie in the National League between the Boston Braves and the Brooklyn Robins in 26 innings, at Braves Field in Boston on May 1, 1920.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] It had become too dark to see the ball (fields did not have lights yet and the sun was setting), and the game was considered a draw.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Played rapidly by modern standards, those 26 innings were completed in 3 hours and 50 minutes.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] As was the custom, the first pitch was thrown at 3:00 p.m., home plate umpire Barry McCormick called the game as lights began appearing in the windows of buildings across the Charles River, just before 7:00 p.m.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest American League game, and tied for the longest major league game by innings which ended with one team winning, was a 7–6 victory by the Chicago White Sox over the Milwaukee Brewers in 25 innings, at Comiskey Park in Chicago in 1984.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The game began at 7:30 p.m. on May 8, 1984, and after scoring early runs both teams scored twice in the 8th inning; but the game was suspended after 17 innings with the score tied 3–3 due to a league curfew rule prohibiting an inning from beginning after 12:59 a.m.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The game was continued the following evening, May 9, 1984, and both teams scored three times in the 21st inning to make the score 6–6; finally, in the bottom of the 25th, the White Sox' Harold Baines hit a walk-off home run to end the contest.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Tom Seaver was the winning pitcher in relief.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] A regularly scheduled game followed, meaning both nights saw 17 innings played; Seaver also started, and won, the second game 5–4.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The official time of the entire 25-inning game was 8 hours, 6 minutes, also a major league record.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Louis Cardinals won a marathon night game that had started the evening before, defeating the host New York Mets, 4 to 3, in the 25th inning after 7 hours and 4 minutes.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] This game is the longest National League contest to be played to a decision and is also tied with the aforementioned Brewers-White Sox game on May 8–9, 1984, for the longest game played to a decision in major league history.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Two Mets errors led to the Cardinals' winning run, starting with an errant pickoff throw that allowed Bake McBride to scamper all the way around from first.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Mets went to the plate 103 times, a record in a major league game; the Cardinals were not far behind with 99 plate appearances.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] All told, a record 175 official at-bats were recorded, with a major-league record 45 runners stranded.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Only a thousand fans were still at Shea Stadium when the game ended at 3:13 a.m. on September 12.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Unlike the American League, the National League had no curfew.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] This was the longest game played to a decision without a suspension.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] On April 15, 1968, the Houston Astros defeated the Mets 1–0 in a 24-inning game at the Houston Astrodome.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The 6-hour, 6-minute contest, which ended with the Astros' Bob Aspromonte hitting a grounder through the legs of Mets shortstop Al Weis in the bottom of the 24th, remains the longest shutout game in major league history.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest American League game to end in a tie was a 24-inning contest between the Detroit Tigers and Philadelphia Athletics on July 21, 1945.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The teams were tied 1–1 when the game was called due to darkness at Shibe Park; the Tigers' Les Mueller had pitched a record 192⁄3 innings, giving up one run before being taken out in the 20th inning.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest game to end in a scoreless tie was a National League contest between the Cincinnati Reds and Brooklyn Dodgers on September 11, 1946.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The teams went 19 innings before darkness fell at Brooklyn's Ebbets Field, forcing the game to be called on account of darkness.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In the American League, the longest 0–0 game was played between the Washington Senators and Detroit Tigers on July 16, 1909.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The game was called after 18 innings due to darkness at Bennett Park in Detroit.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest scoreless period within a completed game came in the April 15, 1968 game between the Astros and Mets which remained scoreless after 23 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Washington Senators became the first team in Major League history to play multiple games of at least 20 innings in a season when they defeated the Minnesota Twins 9–7 in 20 innings on August 9, 1967, after winning a 22-inning game over the Chicago White Sox on June 12 of that year.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] This feat would later be accomplished by the 1971 Oakland Athletics who had games of 21 and 20 innings and the 1989 Los Angeles Dodgers who played two 22-inning contests.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest doubleheader in Major League history was on May 31, 1964.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The San Francisco Giants beat the New York Mets 5–3 in nine innings in the day's first game at Shea Stadium, and then won the nightcap 8–6 after 23 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The two games lasted a combined nine hours, 52 minutes.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Mets' Ed Kranepool played in all 32 innings of the two games; Kranepool had been called up to the team that day after having played in both games of a doubleheader the day before for their Triple-A club in Buffalo.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] On April 5, 2012, the Toronto Blue Jays beat the Cleveland Indians 7–4 in 16 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The five-hour, 14-minute game was the longest Opening Day game in Major League history.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] On June 8, 2013, the Toronto Blue Jays beat the Texas Rangers 4–3 in 18 innings while the Miami Marlins beat the New York Mets 2–1 in 20 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] This was the second time in Major League history that two games of 18 innings or more were played on same day; the first was August 15, 2006.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In the 2013 season, the Arizona Diamondbacks set a major league record by playing 78 extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] This broke the season record of 76 extra innings played by the Minnesota Twins in 1969.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In the 2020 season, and later extended into 2021 and 2022 before being made permanent in 2023, a new rule was added, adding a runner on second to begin each extra inning.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest game played under these rules was a 16-inning game on August 25, 2021, between the Dodgers and Padres in San Diego where the Dodgers won 5–3 after both teams entered extra innings tied at 1 and traded two runs each in the 15th inning.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] He celebrated with his teammates and did not advance to second base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] According to the rules, only one run scored, giving the Mets a 4–3 win over the Atlanta Braves.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest postseason game by innings in MLB history is 18 innings; this has occurred in five games, all of which were decided by a solo home run.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Four of the five 18 inning games involve either the Houston Astros or the Los Angeles Dodgers.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The first 18-inning contest was played between the Atlanta Braves and the Houston Astros on October 9, 2005.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In Game 4 of a National League Division Series in Houston, the Braves (who were trailing the series 2–1 and facing elimination) took a 6–1 lead into the 8th inning.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] A grand slam by Lance Berkman in the bottom of the 8th brought the score to 6–5, and with two outs in the bottom of the 9th, Brad Ausmus homered to tie the game and send it to extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The score remained deadlocked at 6–6 until the 18th, when the Astros' Chris Burke (who entered the game in the 9th inning as a pinch runner) hit a walk-off home run to left to win it, sending Houston to the NLCS.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Roger Clemens, who was brought in to pinch-hit in the 15th and pitched the last three innings in relief, was credited as the winning pitcher in the 5-hour, 50-minute contest.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Adam LaRoche and Tim Hudson played in both of the first two 18-inning games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] This one as Atlanta Braves and the second one as opposing sides of one another with Hudson pitching in both games as the visiting team's starting pitcher.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The second 18-inning game was Game 2 of the 2014 National League Division Series, when the visiting San Francisco Giants defeated the Washington Nationals 2–1.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The game ended just after midnight on October 5, 2014, and lasted 6 hours 23 minutes.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Nationals had been leading 1–0 with two out in the ninth inning, with starter Jordan Zimmermann one out away from a complete-game shutout.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Following a decision by manager Matt Williams to remove Zimmermann with two out after he walked Joe Panik, Washington closer Drew Storen gave up a single to Giants catcher Buster Posey and an RBI double to Pablo Sandoval, scoring Panik to tie the game 1–1.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Posey was thrown out at the plate trying to score the second San Francisco run on Sandoval's double.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] After Sergio Romo retired the Nationals in order in the bottom half, the game went into extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] There was no further scoring until Giants first baseman Brandon Belt led off the top of the 18th inning with a home run.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Hunter Strickland, a September call-up, recorded the save.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Until 2022, this was the only one to go the full 18 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The third 18-inning game was Game 3 of the 2018 World Series.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] It was played on October 26, 2018, between the Boston Red Sox and Los Angeles Dodgers at Dodger Stadium.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Dodgers took a 1–0 lead in the 3rd inning when Joc Pederson homered off of Boston starter Rick Porcello.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Red Sox tied the game in the top of the 8th when Jackie Bradley Jr. hit a solo home run off of Dodgers closer Kenley Jansen.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The game remained deadlocked at 1 until the 13th inning when Brock Holt scored on a throwing error by Dodgers reliever Scott Alexander.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Dodgers subsequently tied it again at 2 in the bottom of the inning, when Max Muncy scored on a throwing error by Red Sox second baseman Ian Kinsler (who had entered the game in the 10th inning as a pinch runner).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The score remained 2–2 until the bottom of the 18th, when Muncy (who had missed a walk-off home run in the 15th inning by mere inches) hit a walk-off solo home run off of Red Sox pitcher Nathan Eovaldi (who was in his 7th inning of relief).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The winning pitcher for the Dodgers was Alex Wood.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] With a duration of 7 hours and 20 minutes, this was also the longest postseason game by time in MLB history.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The fourth 18-inning game was Game 3 of the 2022 American League Division Series.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] It was played on October 15, 2022, between the Houston Astros and Seattle Mariners at T-Mobile Park.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Astros took a 1–0 lead in the top of the 18th inning on a home run by shortstop Jeremy Peña.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Mariners went 1-2-3 in the bottom half of the 18th, allowing a 3-game sweep by the Astros to advance to the American League Championship Series, and it took 6 hours, 22 minutes to finish the longest shutout game in postseason history.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The 17 scoreless innings in a game set a new Major League postseason record.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The fifth and most recent 18-inning game was Game 3 of the 2025 World Series between the Toronto Blue Jays and the Los Angeles Dodgers at Dodger Stadium on October 27, 2025.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Freddie Freeman hit a walk-off solo shot off Brendon Little to end the 6 hour, 39 minute contest with a 6-5 Los Angeles victory.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The 1986 National League Championship Series was notable for its two climactic extra-inning games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] After the Houston Astros and the New York Mets split the first four games of the series, the Mets won Game 5 in 12 innings and Game 6 in 16 innings to claim the pennant.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Angels tied it in the bottom half but in the top of the 11th, Henderson's sacrifice fly off Moore proved to be the winning margin and the Angels lost the game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The series returned to Boston and the Angels were outscored a combined 18–5 in games 6 and 7 to lose the pennant.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Game 6 of the 1986 World Series between the New York Mets and Boston Red Sox went into extra innings as well.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Red Sox scored 2 runs in the top of the 10th inning to take a 5–3 lead and then got two quick outs with no one on base in the bottom of the 10th.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] With the Red Sox one out away from their first world championship in 68 years, reliever Calvin Schiraldi gave up three straight singles (to Gary Carter, Kevin Mitchell, and Ray Knight), with Carter scoring on Knight's single to cut the lead to one run with runners on first and third.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Red Sox manager John McNamara replaced Schiraldi with Bob Stanley, who then threw a two-strike wild pitch to Mookie Wilson to allow Mitchell to score the tying run and move Knight to second base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The wild pitch was particularly notable in that it completely turned the tables on the Red Sox from what they had done while facing the Angels weeks earlier, as they themselves had now blown a situation in which they were one strike away from winning the series.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Wilson subsequently hit a ground ball to first base that rolled through the legs of first baseman Bill Buckner, allowing Knight to score the winning run from second base and sending the Series to a Game 7 where the Mets completed the comeback.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Had Buckner not committed this error, the game would have either remained tied with runners on first and third for the next batter (if Wilson was safe) or would have gone to an 11th inning (if Wilson had been out).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The 1980 National League Championship Series, played between the Houston Astros and the Philadelphia Phillies, had four of its five games go to extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Astros won Games 2 and 3 in 10 and 11 innings respectively, while the Phillies took Games 4 and 5 in 10 innings each.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Game 6 of the 2011 World Series invokes echoes of 1986.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In the bottom of the 9th inning, the Texas Rangers were one strike away from winning their first World Series when David Freese hit a two-run triple to tie the game 7–7 and send the game to extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In the 10th, Josh Hamilton hit a two-run home run to give the Rangers a 9–7 lead, but the Cardinals responded with two runs to tie the game again at 9.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The game ended in the 11th inning when Freese led off with a walk-off solo home run.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Just like the Mets did in 1986, the Cardinals went on to win Game 7 and the championship.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The 2012 American League Division Series between the Baltimore Orioles and the New York Yankees had back-to-back extra-inning games, going 12 and 13 innings respectively.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Yankees won Game 3 on a walk-off home run by Raúl Ibañez and the Orioles returned the favor the next night by winning Game 4.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In the 1995 American League Division Series, the Seattle Mariners and Yankees battled in Game 2 in 15 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Yankees won the game on a two-run walk-off home run by Jim Leyritz, setting the record for longest game in MLB postseason history by time until 2005.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] In Game 5, the Mariners won the game and the series in 11 innings on Edgar Martínez's famous double that scored Ken Griffey Jr.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Until 2011, this was the only LDS game 5 in either league to go into extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The 2014 American League Wild Card Game featured the first extra-inning game in its third year of postseason existence, was won by the Kansas City Royals over the Oakland Athletics in 12 innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest Game 7 in postseason history was during the 1924 World Series where the Washington Senators beat the New York Giants 4–3 in 12 innings to claim the title.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Over the history of the World Series, 69 games have gone to extra innings, setting the following innings-related records.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest major league All-Star Game by time was played on July 15, 2008, at Yankee Stadium, with the American League winning 4–3 in 15 innings after four hours, 50 minutes.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Michael Young hit the walk-off sacrifice fly to win it.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] This was the first time in All-Star game history that the AL won an All-Star Game in extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The previous nine times the National League went 8–0–1 in extra-inning games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The All-Star Game of July 11, 1967, at Anaheim Stadium also lasted 15 innings, but was considerably shorter in terms of elapsed time.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The All-Star Game of July 9, 2002, at Miller Park was controversially declared a 7–7 tie after 11 innings, when both teams ran out of available pitchers.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Since the 2022 All-Star Game, if the All-Star Game is tied after nine innings, the winner will be decided by a home run derby rather than with extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Despite the association with the All-Star Game, this is distinct from the annual home run derby held every year the day before the All-Star Game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The rules differ somewhat from the regular home run derby, with each manager selecting three players to make three swings each to hit as many home runs as possible.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] If a tie remains, sudden death triple-swing rounds will be played until one team outslugs the other.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The winning team will be credited with a run and a hit.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] On November 6, 2010, the record for longest Japan Series game was set in Game 6.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Chiba Lotte Marines and the Chunichi Dragons played 15 innings totaling 5 hours and 43 minutes.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The game ended a 2–2 tie leading to a Game 7 in which the Marines won the game and the championship.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest game in Taiwan Series's history took place in Game 6 on October 24, 2009.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Brother Elephants defeated the Uni-President 7-Eleven Lions 5 to 4 and tied the series 3–3 after 17 innings that totals 6 hours 14 minutes.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The Lions eventually took the title after defeating the Elephants 5 to 2 in Game 7.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The longest college baseball game was played between Texas and Boston College on May 30, 2009, in a regional NCAA Division I Baseball Championship tournament game at Austin, Texas.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Texas won the game, 3–2, in 25 innings as the visiting team under NCAA tournament rules on home-team declaration during a tournament.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The game lasted seven hours and three minutes.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Three years later, another NCAA tournament game passed the 20-inning mark when Kent State defeated Kentucky, 7–6, in 21 innings in an opening-round game at the Gary Regional in Gary, Indiana.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The 1943 Boston Red Sox played an MLB record 31 extra inning games, winning 15 and losing 14, with 2 games tied.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] They played 73 extra innings that season, equivalent to playing an additional eight nine-inning games.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The fewest extra inning games played in a season (dating back to at least 1908) is one, by the 2020 St.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Louis Cardinals, who played only 58 games in a season shortened by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The 2016 Los Angeles Angels played four extra inning games, the fewest in a 162-game season, and lost all four.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The record for most extra inning victories in a season is held by the 1959 Pittsburgh Pirates, who won 19 of their 21 extra inning games (one of the two losses came vs. the Milwaukee Braves in the bottom of the 13th at County Stadium after Harvey Haddix pitched 12 perfect innings).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The convention of the visiting team batting first means that there is no limit to the possible margin of victory for the visitors in extra innings.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] The MLB record is held by the 1983 Texas Rangers, who put up 12 unanswered runs in the top of the 15th inning to defeat the Oakland Athletics by a score of 16–4 on July 3.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/automatic-runner] Conversely, for the home team who bats second, the highest possible margin of victory is four.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] Sportswriter Henry Chadwick is generally credited as the inventor of baseball scorekeeping.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] His basic scorecard and notation have evolved significantly since their advent in the 1870s but they remain the basis for most of what has followed.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] Some symbols and abbreviations are shared by nearly all scorekeeping systems.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] Usually two scorecards (one for each team) are used to score a game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] There is no authoritative set of rules for scorekeeping.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] The traditional method has many variations in its symbols and syntax, but this is a typical example.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] In the traditional method, each cell in the main area of the scoresheet represents the "lifetime" of an offensive player, from at-bat, to baserunner, to being put out, scoring a run, or being left on base.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] When an out is recorded, the combination of defensive players executing that out is recorded.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] If a batter reaches first base, either due to a walk, a hit, or an error, the basepath from home to first base is drawn, and the method described in the lower-righthand corner.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] When a runner advances due to a following batter, it can be noted by the batting position or the uniform number of the batter that advanced the runner.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] This kind of information is not always included by amateur scorers, and there is a lot of variation in notation.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] Project Scoresheet was an organization run by volunteers in the 1980s for the purpose of collecting baseball game data and making it freely available to the public (the data collected by Major League Baseball was and still is not freely available).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] To collect and distribute the data, Project Scoresheet needed a method of keeping score that could be easily input to a computer.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] This limited the language to letters, numbers, and punctuation (no baseball diamonds or other symbols not found on a computer keyboard).
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] The corresponding system was developed by baseball authors and statisticians including Craig Wright and Gary Gillette.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] In addition to the new language introduced by Project Scoresheet, a few major changes were made to the traditional scorecard.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] First, innings of play are not recorded in a one-per-column fashion; instead all boxes are used sequentially and new innings are indicated with a heavy horizontal line.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] This saves considerable space on the card (since no boxes are left blank) and reduces the likelihood of a game requiring a second set of scorecards.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] The second major change is the detailed offensive and defensive in/out system, which allows the scorekeeper to specify very specifically when players enter and leave the game.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] This is vital for attributing events to the proper players.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] Lastly, each "event box" on a Project Scoresheet scorecard is broken down into three sections: before the play, during the play, and after the play.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] All events are put into one of these three slots.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] For example, a stolen base happens "before the play" because it occurs before the batter's at-bat is over.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] A hit is considered "during the play" because it ends the batter's plate appearance, and baserunner movement subsequent to the batter's activity is considered "after the play".
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] The language developed by Project Scoresheet can be used to record trajectories and locations of batted balls and every defensive player who touched the ball, in addition to the basic information recorded by the traditional method.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] With the advent of online baseball event application programming interface feeds, it is now possible to have software generate and update a scorecard in real-time.
[src:baseball-scorekeeping/baseball-scorekeeping] Such scorecards can include a level of detail and precision which would not be practical for a human keeping score manually.
